\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces The multi-turn prompting protocol, illustrated with a LendingClub example. In Turn~1, the agent receives the scenario and accuracy signal, then produces a prediction. In Turn~2, the agent sees its own prediction and decides whether to implement or escalate. The accuracy signal provides the feature-based accuracy from a decision tree trained on the dataset.}}{5}{figure.caption.7}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:protocol}{{2}{5}{The multi-turn prompting protocol, illustrated with a LendingClub example. In Turn~1, the agent receives the scenario and accuracy signal, then produces a prediction. In Turn~2, the agent sees its own prediction and decides whether to implement or escalate. The accuracy signal provides the feature-based accuracy from a decision tree trained on the dataset}{figure.caption.7}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Escalation rate versus predictive accuracy for all six models across four datasets (with signals, no thinking). Each model exhibits a distinct escalation personality, varying in both overall escalation level and sensitivity to accuracy. Error bars show $\pm 1$ standard error.}}{5}{figure.caption.8}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:esc_curves}{{3}{5}{Escalation rate versus predictive accuracy for all six models across four datasets (with signals, no thinking). Each model exhibits a distinct escalation personality, varying in both overall escalation level and sensitivity to accuracy. Error bars show $\pm 1$ standard error}{figure.caption.8}{}}
